TriboModel Class Definition¶

class Energy.Sources.Tribo.Tribo.TriboModel[source]¶

Bases: openmdao.main.component.Component

The TriboModel is a wrapper for a power and cost calculation in regard to implementing a tile-based triboelectric system. The PaveGen solution was the primary intended use, although there is very little available information for it. There are some articles, such as _this: http://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/power-generating-tiles-renewable-energy one that seems to cause confusion on how to calculate the power generation. The approach taken is to create a detailed simulation of the pedestrian movement through the aquarium to estimate the number of steps we would see on a given tile, then use that information in the calculation of power generation.

The current assumption for power calculation is that the quoted 7 watts per step is only over a short period of time, like 1 second. You can use this to calculate what that is in kWh. This can be used with the yearly steps per tile to provide some performance output for a design decision on the number of tiles, along with the cost impact of that decision.

Relies on input values from the PedestrianModel for use in calculating the power generation.

execute()[source]¶

The method for an OpenMDAO component that is required to be filled out with the internal behavior, and is called each time OpenMDAO has changed the input values. After execution, the new output values are then read from the component. This component executes to functions; one to calculate power, and one to calculate the initial capital cost associated with the configuration of the input values.

Returns:None

TriboModel Calculations¶

Energy.Sources.Tribo.calc_tribo.calc_power(tileCount, pedStepsPerTile, tileEff, tilePower, timePerStep)[source]¶

Calc_power computes the total number of steps that will occur across all tiles for this given design configuration. The total number of steps is affected by the number of tiles and the pedestrian model that simulates both on and off season steps per tile.

Note

The vendor advertises watts generated per step, not kWh. So we convert to energy by assuming a step generates power at the stated power for a fixed period of time, timePerStep

Parameters:
  • tileCount – A design variable for how many tiles you would want to purchase
  • pedStepsPerTile – An uncertainty for the number of expected steps per tile over a year
  • tileEff – The amount of actual useful energy based on the claimed
  • tilePower – The claimed power return when one person steps on a tile
  • timePerStep – The duration of power generation for one step
Returns:

The total energy generated in a year for the input design configuration
Energy.Sources.Tribo.calc_tribo.calc_cost(tileUnitCost, tileCount, mgtTileUnitCost)[source]¶

Calc_cost computes the cost of a triboelectric system based on the PedGen pricing model. There are affects to cost based on the number of units you purchase, which affects how many management tiles are needed as well.

Parameters:
  • tileUnitCost – A cost per regular tile type when purchased in bulk
  • tileCount – The whole number count of tiles to be installed
  • mgtTileUnitCost – The cost per management tile
Returns:

The cost of purchasing and installation of the tribo system

TriboModel Optimization¶

class Energy.Sources.Tribo.Tribo.TriboOptimization[source]¶

Bases: openmdao.main.assembly.Assembly

Implements an assembly to contain the TriboModel component, and run optimizations on it stand-alone with the pyOpt plugin of optimization drivers. Implements a caserecorder so that you can investigate the results afterwards. This assembly will show up automatically when using openmdao gui, or can be used directly in another python script as you would use a regular python class.

configure()[source]¶

This method must be filled in with the desired configuration for any custom OpenMDAO Assembly. This Assembly is used to load the TriboModel for execution, sets up a pyOpt optimizer, configures a CSV recorder to record inputs and outputs to tribo_optimization.csv, then configures parameters, an objective, and a constraint. This isolated optimization can be used to ensure the model is working correctly before integrating it into a larger model.
